observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require the Municipal Engineer/Project Engineer and Municipal Accountant to:

coordinate with the DAR Central Office to facilitate compliance with the conditions to allow reconciliation and settlement of the accounts relevant to ARCP II projects;


make the corresponding journal entries to record the completed projects and adjust the Due to NGAs and other relevant accounts.

We recommended that the LGU, thru the Mayor and other concerned LGU Officials:

submit to COA, the guidelines for the grant of educational assistance to the recipients and the complete supporting documents for the grants for 2014.    Failure to comply with the same may result to audit suspensions;

conduct needs assessment for education of every barangay to ensure equitable distribution and availability of the grant to eligible recipients;

establish a more concrete and organized scholarship program, taking into consideration the needs identified and the availability of funds for the purpose.

We recommended that the Management:
Convene with the representative of the WSP and communicate the lapses as to compliance with the provisions set out in Section 8.3 and Section 7 of the MOA;
Agree in writing whether the responsibility of collecting the outstanding MILAWUD consumptions shall be continued by the WSP or reverted to the Office of the Municipal Treasurer;
Determine and enforce other control measures to ensure the collection of the remaining arrears from concerned MILAWUD consumers;
Require the WSP to submit the summary report of water consumption starting from its date of operation from July 2021 until December 2021 and January to December 2022 so that the Municipal Accountant will be able to bill the unpaid franchise fee, and thereafter a monthly report of the water consumption in CY 2023 to allow the Office of the Municipal Accountant to include in the billing statement the franchise fee due for the period;
Direct the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to monitor the payment received from the WSP and submit the related reports to the Office of the Municipal Accountant to properly account for the payment and reflect any adjustments in the billing statement; and
Prospectively, timely coordinate any concern to the WSP to properly address any issues concerning the agreements and conditions laid down in the MOA.

We recommended that Management and all others concerned in the procurement, inspection of deliveries, processing, approval, and payment of claims:
Provide adequate and proper documentation for procurements of infrastructures and goods;
Withhold the 10 percent retention money in accordance with Sections 5.3.c and 6 of Annex “E” of the RIRR of RA No. 9184;
Scrutinize the bidding documents submitted by the bidders, and ensure compliance with the eligibility requirements provided in the RIRR of RA No. 9184, which includes, among others, an NFCC at least equal to the ABC; and
Review the existing roles and responsibilities delegated and/or assumed by the different LGU offices and its key officers, and delineate incompatible or complementing functions, as appropriate.

We recommended that Management:
Strictly require the full and prompt settlement of the cash advances as provided in the pertinent COA Circulars, otherwise, enforce the appropriate sanctions;
Send final demand letters to persons with outstanding cash advances to immediately settle their accounts;
Stop or refuse additional cash advances to officers and/or employees unless previous ones have been settled; and
Request write-off of unliquidated balances of deceased accountable officers in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005.

We recommended that the Management:
Through the Office of the Municipal Accountant, confirm with the DOF-MDFO and the PVB the balance of existing loans and the related charges to the Municipality to ensure that the recorded balances in the books are accurate, and the charges imposed upon the LGU are valid;
With the aid of the Office of the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator:
Prospectively, conduct a thorough study of the proposed developmental and socio-economic projects, and present the same for the concurrence of the local government development council;
Together with the Implementing Office, monitor and evaluate the implementation of the different development programs, projects, and activities in the Municipality by preparing a report showing the actual accomplishment or status of the projects vis-à-vis the target, to ensure effective and efficient use of the funds; and
Develop plans to address the problems which prevent the continued operation of the existing projects or determine alternative use thereof to maximize its purpose.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct the MEO to explain the determination of the contract duration specified in the Program of Works / Contract Agreement for all the LDF infrastructure projects undertaken for CY 2022;
Prepare the PERT/CPM network diagram before the preparation of the Bidding Documents to ensure that the contract time computation is based on the PERT/CPM Network Diagram, particularly prepared by the MEO;
Direct the Bids and Awards Committee to ensure that the contract time computation is supported with a PERT/CPM Network Diagram;
Require MEO officers/personnel concerned to provide a program of works and needs analysis for each of the infrastructure projects included in the Local Development Plan (LDP) so that a more realistic estimate of costs is presented as the basis for the approved appropriations/budget;
Ensure that no program of work for any project shall be approved without adequate detailed engineering;
Impose equivalent liquidated damages in case of Contractor’s delay/default and suspension of work of construction projects shall be granted based only on grounds authorized under the RIRR of RA 9184, otherwise, the transaction may be suspended in audit; and
Direct the MLDC to ensure that projects being considered in the LDP were supported with complete detailed engineering particularly the Program of Work with PERT/CPM Network Diagram before its inclusion in the LDP.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct the Local Development Council to provide a document/justification in writing on the shift of purpose of the project from the public market into an evacuation center and multi-purpose building;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to provide legal basis or authorization on the disbursement and charging of the additional expenses for the construction of the evacuation center formerly constructed as a public market in the project improvement of the multi-purpose building;
Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO) and Municipal Local Development Council (MLDC) and Municipal Engineering Office to explain in writing the implementation of two projects (construction and improvement) at the same time while referring to the same project only; and
Direct the MPDO to ensure that projects identified to be included in the LDP were sufficiently described in complete and specific details like construction of the second floor, improvement of the first floor or evacuation center or multi-purpose building or slaughterhouse, etc., to avoid confusion.

We recommended that the Management:
Stop the discretionary hiring of consultants, and observe the proper procurement process in the hiring of the same as provided in the pertinent provisions of the Manual of Procedures for the Procurement of Consulting Services, and the RIRR of RA No. 9184;
Carefully assess the need of hiring a consultant to avoid duplication of functions, and prepare the requisite Terms of Reference;
Prepare and submit all relevant supporting documents from procurement until payment of consultants; and
Furnish the Audit Team with the written authority of the Solicitor General and written concurrence of the COA on the hiring of a legal consultant.

We recommended that the Management:
Issue an Acknowledgement Receipt for in-kind donations for DRRM signed by the Head of the Agency or his/ her authorized representative;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Registry of Donated Relief Goods – DRRM, to reflect the full cost of ending inventory of goods/vaccines received and issued, and record in the books the cost of donated PPE less its total accumulated depreciation if there is any;
Instruct the Property and Supply Unit to inspect the donations to the Municipality and maintain the Property Cards of the same for check and balance with the accounting Unit;
Instruct the RHU to prepare and submit a monthly report to the Accounting Office on the receipt, issuance, and balances of vaccines and other inventories directly received from outside sources; as well as to the Property Custodian in terms of receipt of inventories received to record its receipt; and
Instruct the DRRM to prepare the reports/ records expected of them in terms of in-kind donations as prescribed in the Circular.

We recommended that Management direct the GFPS to:
Use the prescribed GPB format, and communicate in writing any changes therein to the DILG;
Conduct the appropriate HGDG tests on the planned and implemented major programs of the LGU to determine its relevance, impact, and attributable costs to GAD;
Prepare a GAD Accomplishment Report based on the GAD Plan and Budget previously reviewed and endorsed by DILG, fill out columns therein with appropriate and adequate information, and attach relevant supporting documents; and
Implement a defined monitoring and evaluation system to properly assess the status and impact of GAD PPAs on gender mainstreaming.

We recommended that Management direct the:

Municipal Development Council to ensure that PPAs in the Local Development Plan are supported with the necessary in-depth study and planning documents before its inclusion in the Plan to warrant the possible attainment of the project within the year;


Municipal Engineer, and other Implementing Offices to provide for the reason(s) for the non-completion and/or non-implementation of the identified priority projects above;


Municipal Engineer, Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator, and other Implementing Offices, to ensure the optimum utilization of the 20% Development fund through the completion and accomplishment of the priority projects identified in the Local Development Plan; and


Refrain from identifying and including PPAs in the Local Development Plan in general categories, rather should be specifically identified supported by plan that would ensure its attainment.

We recommended that Management:

Submit a copy of the Executive Order on the constitution of an Inventory Committee, which shall be composed of adequate number of members, and include at least one member each from the Office of the Municipal Accountant and Office of the Municipal Treasurer;

Require the head of various offices to oversee the conduct of physical count of existing PPEs found in their respective offices and prepare the report using Annex A of the cited Circular for verification of the Inventory Committee;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to update the RPCPPE using the data provided by various offices to reflect the actual count and value of the PPE items maintained by the Municipality; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain PPELCs for all items of PPE and ensure that the total balance of PPELCs tally with the balances of controlling PPE accounts in the General Ledger.

We recommended that management:

Prepare a clear, comprehensive and well defined implementing guidelines on the LGU AICs program and all other assistance and institutionalize the same to formalize its adoption to ensure that only qualified and eligible indigent beneficiaries were given the type, kind and amount of assistance they needed after the assessment, validation and recommendation of the MSWDO;

Initiate a comprehensive review of the LGU’s Program on AICS and all other assistance to the poor, vulnerable and marginalized individuals and families so that the LGU’s AICs and other assistance program attains its purpose and its benefits redound to as many qualified and needy clients the fund can accommodate;

Thru the MSWDO, to conduct a prior study, screening, verification, assessment and recommendation of qualified recipients of the program and install and implement a control mechanism that would monitor on the duplication of beneficiaries and assistance, qualification and eligibility of beneficiaries and funds available for disbursement;

Thru the MSWDO, to install a database encoding system like a Crisis Intervention Monitoring system as stated in the DSWD guidelines instead of a logbook that can easily summarize data in a particular period as well as fast checking of names of beneficiaries to avoid duplication and minimize manual errors committed in the screening and evaluation process; and

Thru the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure that disbursement vouchers are attached with complete and adequate documentation to support the transactions pertaining to AICS and all other assistance before its recording and release.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly require full settlement of the existing cash advances that remained outstanding for more than one calendar year, otherwise enforce the appropriate sanctions;

Send final demand letters to persons not anymore connected with the LGU to settle the balance of their cash advances;

Request write-off of unliquidated balances of deceased accountable officers in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005; and

Ensure that the granting, utilization and liquidation of all cash advances be in accordance with the above-mentioned Circular.

We recommended that Management:

Convene with the LSB and agree on the timeline of the preparation and approval of the SEF budget following the indicative period of relevant activities in the cited Joint Circular;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to work together in the preparation of the certified statement of SEF income to properly establish a more realistic basis of the available fund for appropriation;

Require the LSB to submit a project proposal for the acquisition of the 75 inches Smart Flat Screen TV to establish the purpose of the purchase and to ensure its utilization for priority programs and projects of the Municipal School Board;

Direct the LSB to explain regarding the purchase of items totaling ₱68,648.00 which did not fall under the priority spending chargeable against the SEF;

Require the LSB to present the proposed expenditures for the budget year in detail, by PAP, by allotment class and per school; and

Remind the LSB to review the budget and its components to ensure that the fund will be utilized for priority programs and projects and will be prepared in accordance with the requirements of the relevant laws, and regulations.

We recommended that the Management:

Direct the Environmental Management Specialist to review and update annually the provisions of the 10-Year Ecological Solid Waste Management Plan, and ensure compliance to the requirements of the DENR-EMB V to facilitate its prompt approval and implementation;

Consider the inclusion of representatives from the various industries or group cited in the Act to further improve its plans through the integration of policies and programs which may developed through consultations with these sectors;

Coordinate with the DENR and the Environment Management Bureau for possible solution or alternatives for the final disposal of their residual wastes, pending the development of a long term disposal facility or sanitary landfill in the Municipality; and

Work closely with the officials of the barangays to ensure that the Municipal policies on solid waste management are properly communicated and implemented at the barangay level to ensure that their solid waste management practice are supportive of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:

instruct the Collectors/Tellers to remit their collections daily and intact;

direct the Liquidating Officer to verify the Report of Collections and Deposits as to initial balances on hand, receipts, sales and issues, and the new balances on hand; to make a physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the Collector/Teller; to check the same to the new balances on hand column; and to count the money turned over to him before signing the certification and receipt portion of all copies of the Report of Collections and Deposits;

require the Municipal Treasurer, as the head of the Treasury Office, to exercise proper management, particularly to impose strong internal control on collections and deposits, of the funds of the LGU; and

advise the Municipal Treasurer, as well as the Collectors/Tellers and Liquidating Officer, to look into the 183 identified transactions to specifically identify the root cause of the unusual balance and rectify and avoid the same in the future.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Treasurer to: 

produce the missing AFs or determine the status of the unaccounted forms and provide evidence to support its issuance, cancellation or existence;

monitor the inventory of accountable forms and make a periodic reconciliation of the actual inventory and the records; 

prepare, maintain and periodically update record books, Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms (RAAF) and other relevant reports;

strictly adhere to the provisions of the above cited Manual and other relevant rules and regulations; and

initiate administrative sanctions to those employees responsible for the unaccounted AFs.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Assessor to:

discontinue adopting the stripping method of assessment in determining the value of commercial lots as provided for in the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations;

update the Field Appraisal and Assessment Sheets (FAASs) of those properties in which FAASs remain to be not updated for a long period of time, even when there exists no transaction;

make sure that the fair market values of the real properties, including the improvements, are properly reflected in the tax declarations and FAASs;

conduct actual inspection of real properties whenever doubt arises as to the sworn statement filed by the declarant as to the true value of their property;

prepare a complete copy of the Assessment Rolls in order to properly account for the real properties located in the Municipality; and

coordinate and follow up with the Provincial Government of Camarines Sur as to the status of enforcement of the General Revision, in order to avoid the lax imposition of the supposedly increase in tax collections.

We recommended that Management require:

the MBMA president to regularly submit reports regarding the operation of the project to proper LGU officials;

the MSWDO strictly monitor the operations of the Bigasan ng Masa by requiring financial records and other documents that will support its operations;

ensure that the procedures contained in the approved project are properly carried out wherein any inconsistency thereto be appropriately addressed; and

the strict observance of the rules and regulations in the implementation and utilization of funds granted by National Agencies.

